            <p><hi rend="initialcap">C</hi>ASE.—<name type="person" key="71">Sergeant
                        D. H. Gleason</name>, <name type="organization" key="80">Co. H, 1st
                        Massachusetts Cavalry</name>, aged 28 years, was thrown from his horse in a
                    charge at <name type="BATTLE" key="249">Gettysburg</name>, <date type="injury" when="1863-07-01">July 1st, 1863</date>, and received a very severe
                    concussion of the brain. He was sent to the hospital at the <name type="hospital" key="88">Cavalry Depot at Camp Stoneman</name>, Washington.
                    After recovering from the symptoms of concussion, he suffered from persistent
                    pain in the head, and on <date type="transfer" when="1864-03-07">March 7th,
                        1864</date>, he was sent to <name type="hospital" key="152">Finley Hospital</name>,
                        Washington. He recovered, and returned to duty <date type="duty" when="1864-10-01">October 1st, 1864</date>.   The case is reported by the late
                        <name type="person" key="72">Surgeon G. L. Pancoast</name>, <name type="organization" key="132">U. S. V.</name></p>            
